1. Core Architecture: The Flex Container & Flex Items
To activate Flexbox, you must apply display: flex; or display: inline-flex; to a parent wrapper element.

Flex Container: The parent element wrapping the items.

Flex Items: The immediate, direct child elements sitting inside that parent container.

The Two Layout Axes
Flexbox rules rely completely on a grid tracking axis coordinate system:

Main Axis: The primary directional vector along which your flex items line up.

Cross Axis: The axis perpendicular to the main axis. If the main axis runs horizontally, the cross axis runs vertically.

2. Parent Container Properties (Flex Container)
A. Establishing Direction (flex-direction)
Determines the direction of the main axis and how items stack up.

row (Default): Items align horizontally from left to right.

row-reverse: Items align horizontally from right to left.

column: Items stack vertically from top to bottom.

column-reverse: Items stack vertically from bottom to top.

B. Wrapping Content (flex-wrap)
By default, flex items will always squeeze tightly onto a single line to prevent layout breaks. This property controls line breaks.

nowrap (Default): Forces all items onto a single line, even if they shrink or overflow the container boundary.

wrap: Automatically wraps overflowing elements onto a fresh, adjacent line track.

wrap-reverse: Wraps elements onto adjacent lines in reverse chronological order.

📝 Shorthand Note: You can combine direction and wrapping into a single property using flex-flow:

CSS
.container { flex-flow: row wrap; }
C. Main Axis Alignment (justify-content)
Controls how items distribute alignment space along the Main Axis.

flex-start (Default): Groups items tightly at the beginning of the axis.

flex-end: Groups items tightly at the terminal end of the axis.

center: Centers items exactly in the middle of the axis line.

space-between: Pushes the first and last items to the outer edges, distributing remaining space evenly between them.

space-around: Distributes identical buffer space on both sides of every single item (causing internal gaps to appear double the width of edge margins).

space-evenly: Distributes completely equal space between all elements and container borders.

D. Cross Axis Alignment (align-items)
Controls how items align along the Cross Axis for a single track row.

stretch (Default): Stretches child items to completely fill the cross-axis height of the parent box container.

flex-start: Aligns items at the starting edge of the cross axis.

flex-end: Aligns items at the terminal edge of the cross axis.

center: Centers items perfectly along the cross axis line.

baseline: Aligns items so that their text baselines line up perfectly.

E. Multi-Line Alignment (align-content)
Aligns the track lines themselves along the cross axis only when elements wrap onto multiple lines. (Has zero effect on single-row layouts).

Values mimic justify-content rules: flex-start, flex-end, center, space-between, space-around, stretch.

3. Child Element Properties (Flex Items)
A. Manual Reordering (order)
Allows you to override the natural order of elements written in your HTML file without modifying the raw markup markup.

Default Value: 0

Behavior: Accepts positive or negative integers. Elements with lower order values display first (e.g., an item with order: -1; snaps to the front line).

B. Scaling Proportions (flex-grow & flex-shrink)
flex-grow: Defines an item's ability to grow if extra space is available. flex-grow: 2; grows at double the rate of a sibling set to 1.

flex-shrink: Defines an item's ability to shrink if space is constricted. 0 prevents shrinking entirely.

C. Base Footprint (flex-basis)
Defines the initial default size dimension of a flex item box before remaining container spaces are distributed. It acts like an intelligent alternative to hardcoded width/height constraints.

Default: auto

D. Isolated Cross Alignment (align-self)
Allows an individual child element to completely break away from the global align-items rule specified on its parent container.

Accepts standard cross alignment parameters (flex-start, flex-end, center, baseline, stretch).

Practical Blueprint Code Example
HTML
<div class="flex-parent">
  <div class="box">Item 1</div>
  <div class="box intermediate">Item 2 (Overriding global center alignment)</div>
  <div class="box">Item 3</div>
</div>
CSS
* {
  margin: 0;
  padding: 0;
  box-sizing: border-box;
}

.flex-parent {
  display: flex;
  flex-direction: row;
  justify-content: space-between; /* Spreads items end-to-end horizontally */
  align-items: center;            /* Centers items vertically */
  height: 200px;
  background-color: #f0f0f0;
}

.box {
  background-color: #007bff;
  color: white;
  padding: 20px;
}

/* Isolate a single item to break away from parent cross-axis rules */
.box.intermediate {
  align-self: flex-end; /* Snaps strictly to the bottom container line track */
}